---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import PageHeader from "../components/PageHeader.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="CapitalBench Scoring"
  description="How CapitalBench compares AI model portfolio returns with the S&P 500 in weekly and monthly tests."
>
  <PageHeader
    eyebrow="Scoring"
    title="How Scores Work"
    summary="Each model's portfolio return is compared with the S&P 500 over the same one-week or one-month test."
  />
  <section class="section doc-layout">
    <article class="doc-body">
      <h2>Public Score</h2>
      <p>
        The public score is the model portfolio return minus the S&amp;P 500 return over the same test period. Each
        model gets one saved portfolio for a test, and that portfolio is what appears on the public scoreboard.
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>Single-pick return: selected option ending price divided by starting price, minus one.</li>
        <li>Portfolio return: weighted sum of holding returns, using the submitted allocation percentages.</li>
        <li>Return versus S&P 500: portfolio return minus S&P 500 return.</li>
        <li>Regret: best available asset return minus the model's return, when full asset-list prices exist.</li>
        <li>Cash comparison: whether the model's return beats a cash return.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Price Inputs</h2>
      <p>
        Starting and ending prices come from the test rules. Starting prices may be published while a test is pending.
        Ending prices and final returns are withheld until the test period is over and the scoring job has produced the
        result files.
      </p>
      <div class="formula-grid">
        <div>
          <span>Single-pick return</span>
          <code>(ending_price / starting_price) - 1</code>
        </div>
        <div>
          <span>Portfolio return</span>
          <code>sum(weight * option_return)</code>
        </div>
        <div>
          <span>Return vs S&amp;P 500</span>
          <code>portfolio_return - sp500_return</code>
        </div>
        <div>
          <span>Regret</span>
          <code>best_asset_return - portfolio_return</code>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2>Overall Results</h2>
      <p>
        Overall results average a model's return versus the S&amp;P 500 across completed tests where that model
        participated. Models are not backfilled into earlier tests; they begin accumulating public history only from
        the tests where they were actually run.
      </p>
      <p>
        The overall view is intentionally simple. It reports participation count, average return versus S&amp;P 500, and
        related completed-test aggregates. It does not introduce hidden weighting, qualified tiers, or a single combined
        score that merges public picks and consistency checks.
      </p>

      <h2>Consistency Tests</h2>
      <p>
        Consistency tests summarize repeated calls with the same saved test input. They measure whether a model tends to
        make the same pick under identical conditions.
      </p>
      <p>
        These repeated-call checks are not mixed into the main scoreboard because the public contest uses one saved
        portfolio per model.
      </p>

      <h2>Pending Tests</h2>
      <p>
        Pending tests can show model portfolios, confidence values, rationale summaries, starting prices, and proof hashes.
        After at least one weekly price snapshot exists, a test page may also show interim return tracking versus
        S&amp;P 500. That chart is explicitly provisional and separate from the final scoreboard. Rank, regret, and final
        return versus S&amp;P 500 remain withheld until ending prices are present and the scorer publishes the result files.
      </p>
    </article>
    <aside class="side-panel">
      <strong>No qualified tier</strong>
      <p>
        The public site intentionally avoids provisional tiers, maturity labels, and weighted mega-scores. A row is
        either pending, public result, overall result, or consistency check.
      </p>
    </aside>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
